{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Jersey", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in New Jersey}}\n{{Current||current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Jersey\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = COVID 19 cases in New Jersey by County.svg\n| legend1         = Counties by number of positive cases in New Jersey as of March 27:{{legend|#510000|750+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#900000|500\u2013749 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#c80200|250\u2013499 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|100\u2013249 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| location        = [[New Jersey]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 4, 2020\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 22,255\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 355\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://covid19.nj.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' was confirmed to have reached the [[U.S. state]] of '''[[New Jersey]]''' with a case reported in [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]] on March 4, 2020. As of April 1, 2020, there were 22,255 positive cases and 355 deaths in the state.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.gov/health/cd/topics/covid2019_dashboard.shtml|title=Department of Health {{!}} Communicable Disease Service {{!}} New Jersey COVID-19 Dashboard|website=www.nj.gov|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315143113/https://www.nj.gov/health/cd/topics/covid2019_dashboard.shtml|archive-date=2020-03-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.gov/health/cd/topics/covid2019_dashboard.shtml|title=Department of Health {{!}} Communicable Disease Service {{!}} New Jersey COVID-19 Dashboard|website=www.nj.gov|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, Governor [[Phil Murphy]] declared a state of emergency. A day later, schools and universities began closing and switching classes to online. Also on March&nbsp;10, the first person in the state died from the disease. Six days later, a statewide curfew began, and all casinos, gyms, and movie theaters were closed; restaurants and bars were only allowed to remain open for delivery. On March&nbsp;21, the number of cases in the state surpassed 1,000. Governor Murphy announced a statewide [[stay-at-home order]] that all non-essential businesses in the state would be closed indefinitely by 9 p.m. that day.\n\n==Timeline==\n\n===March===\n==== March 4\u201310 ====\n[[File:2020-03-09 \u2014 Empty shelves NJ 02.jpg|thumb|Empty shelves in a New Jersey store in March 2020.]]\nOn March 4, Governor [[Phil Murphy]] and Lieutenant Governor [[Sheila Oliver]] released a joint statement announcing the state's first case, a presumptive positive test result in a man in his 30s who had been hospitalized in [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]] since March 3.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=New Jersey announces first presumptive case of COVID-19 coronavirus|url=https://www.fox5ny.com/news/new-jersey-announces-first-presumptive-case-of-covid-19-coronavirus|work=[[WNYW]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=Fort Lee man with first NJ coronavirus case being treated at Hackensack Medical Center|last1=Sobko|first1=Katie|last2=Washburn|first2=Lindy|last3=Cattafi|first3=Kristie|work=[[The Record (North Jersey)|The Record]], Woodland Park, N.J.|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/bergen/2020/03/04/nj-gov-phil-murphy-bergen-county-nj-first-confirmed-case-coronavirus-covid-19/4958681002/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305060925/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/bergen/2020/03/04/nj-gov-phil-murphy-bergen-county-nj-first-confirmed-case-coronavirus-covid-19/4958681002/|archive-date=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, officials announced that they were investigating a second presumptive case of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=ltgovoliver|number=1235659179580256256|date=5 March 2020|language=en|title=We now have our second presumptive case of coronavirus in New Jersey.}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, officials announced a third presumptive case of coronavirus in [[Camden County, New Jersey|Camden County]] and a fourth case in Bergen County.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alex |first1=Sergio BichaoDan |title=3rd coronavirus case confirmed in NJ \u2014 now in Camden County |url=https://nj1015.com/3rd-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-nj-this-one-in-camden-county/ |website=New Jersey 101.5 |language=en |access-date=2020-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307141900/https://nj1015.com/3rd-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-nj-this-one-in-camden-county/ |archive-date=2020-03-07 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.gov/governor/news/news/562020/approved/20200306d.shtml|title=Joint Statement from Governor Murphy, Acting Governor Oliver, and Commissioner Persichilli on Fourth Presumptive Positive Case of Novel Coronavirus in New Jersey|access-date=2020-03-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307100439/https://www.nj.gov/governor/news/news/562020/approved/20200306d.shtml|archive-date=2020-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, two presumptive positive cases were confirmed in East Brunswick and Edison, bringing the total to six.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newjersey.news12.com/story/41867312/2-more-presumptive-positive-coronavirus-cases-identified-in-nj-total-at-6|title=2 more 'presumptive positive' coronavirus cases identified in NJ; total at 6|website=newjersey.news12.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308183447/http://newjersey.news12.com/story/41867312/2-more-presumptive-positive-coronavirus-cases-identified-in-nj-total-at-6|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref> Several schools and school districts announced closings or schedule modifications by the 8th due to the impact of the virus.<!--Frisch school in Paramus, Mount Olive School District, South Brunswick, Cranford--><ref name=NewYorkJerseyClosings38>[https://www.pix11.com/news/coronavirus/schools-closing-in-ny-nj-amid-spread-of-covid-19 List of schools closing in NY, NJ amid spread of COVID-19] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309053159/https://www.pix11.com/news/coronavirus/schools-closing-in-ny-nj-amid-spread-of-covid-19 |date=2020-03-09 }} [[PIX 11]]</ref>\n\nOn March 9, Governor Murphy declared a state of emergency in New Jersey as the number of cases grew to 11.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2020/03/09/coronavirus-update-nj-cases-new-jersey-11/5000370002/|title=Coronavirus update: Here's what we know about NJ's 11 cases as state of emergency declared|date=2020-03-09|website=northjersey.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310091826/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2020/03/09/coronavirus-update-nj-cases-new-jersey-11/5000370002/|archive-date=2020-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, state officials announced the first death in New Jersey to be in Bergen County. A resident of [[Little Ferry, New Jersey|Little Ferry]], 69-year-old John Brennan was the first to succumb to the virus in New Jersey. He had underlying health conditions and was taken to [[Hackensack University Medical Center]] where he died of a heart attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.app.com/story/news/new-jersey/2020/03/10/nj-coronavirus-cases-tuesday-state-total/5009352002/|title=Horse trainer from Little Ferry is first in NJ to die of coronavirus|last=McDonald|first=Terrence T.|website=Asbury Park Press|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> It would come to light days later that the man was connected to cluster of coronavirus among a New Jersey family that would kill 4 family members.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.app.com/story/news/2020/03/16/coronavirus-freehold-religious-teacher-new-jerseys-second-death-virus/5057226002/|title=Coronavirus: Freehold religious teacher is NJ 2nd death; linked to fatal Bergen case|last=Schubert|first=Keith|website=Asbury Park Press|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/19/health/new-jersey-coronavirus-family-members-killed/index.html|title=Coronavirus kills 4 family members and sickens others after a dinner in New Jersey|first1=Theresa|last1=Waldrop|first2=Melanie|last2=Schuman|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320004641/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/19/health/new-jersey-coronavirus-family-members-killed/index.html|archive-date=2020-03-20|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 10, [[Rutgers University]], [[New Jersey Institute of Technology]], [[Seton Hall]], [[Stevens Institute of Technology]], [[The College of New Jersey]], and [[Monmouth University]] announced that all of their classes would be switched to an online format.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/nj-coronavirus-latest-on-schools-and-colleges-that-are-closing-or-changing-schedules-tuesday-march-10.html|title=N.J. coronavirus: Latest on schools and colleges that are closing or changing schedules|first=Jeff Goldman &#124; NJ Advance Media for|last=NJ.com|date=March 10, 2020|website=nj|accessdate=March 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312141716/https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/nj-coronavirus-latest-on-schools-and-colleges-that-are-closing-or-changing-schedules-tuesday-march-10.html|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/10/rutgers-cancels-classes-tells-students-to-leave-campus-due-to-coronavirus-fears/|title=Rutgers cancels classes, tells students to leave campus due to coronavirus fears|last=Algar|first=Selim|date=2020-03-10|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311151501/https://nypost.com/2020/03/10/rutgers-cancels-classes-tells-students-to-leave-campus-due-to-coronavirus-fears/|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 11\u201317 ====\nOn March 14, Governor Murphy announced on Twitter an additional 19 confirmed cases of COVID-19, bringing the cumulative total of confirmed cases to 69.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/GovMurphy/status/1238889377121669120 |title=Governor Murphy Tweet from March 14 |access-date=2020-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314193354/https://twitter.com/GovMurphy/status/1238889377121669120 |archive-date=2020-03-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 14, the mayor of [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]] declared a mandatory nightly curfew.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/coronavirus/hoboken-mayor-imposes-mandatory-nightly-curfew-limits-restaurant-access/2327250/ | title = Hoboken Mayor Imposes Mandatory Nightly Curfew; Restaurants Limited to Takeout, Delivery Orders | publisher = NBC New York | date = 2020-03-14 | accessdate = 2020-03-14 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200316132436/https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/coronavirus/hoboken-mayor-imposes-mandatory-nightly-curfew-limits-restaurant-access/2327250/ | archive-date = 2020-03-16 | url-status = live }}</ref> A second death was reported on March 14 in Monmouth County: 56-year-old Rita Fusco-Jackson of [[Freehold Township, New Jersey|Freehold]] died of the virus the prior evening after being treated at [[CentraState Medical Center]]. She was the first of four members of a family to die in what would become a cluster of nearly 10 cases that was spread among a single family.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/GovMurphy/status/1238981212678619136|title=Sad to announce our second death of an individual with #COVID19|last=Murphy|first=Governor Phil|date=2020-03-14|website=@GovMurphy|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315002100/https://twitter.com/GovMurphy/status/1238981212678619136|archive-date=2020-03-15|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.app.com/story/news/health/2020/03/19/coronavirus-nj-fusco-family-covid-19-claims-3-family-members-roots-freehold/2876924001/|title=Coronavirus in NJ: Sadness, fear as COVID-19 claims 4 family members with Freehold roots|last=Goudsward|first=Andrew J.|last2=Cervenka|first2=Susanne|website=Asbury Park Press|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Murphy announced via Twitter that another 31 cases had been confirmed in the state, bringing the cumulative total to 98 positive cases. He also stated on a New York City radio station that he was considering a statewide curfew, following the one implemented in Hoboken.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2020/03/15/coronavirus-nj-statewide-curfew-spread-phil-murphy/|title=Coronavirus In New Jersey: COVID-19 Cases Jumps To 98 As Officials Considering Statewide Curfew|date=2020-03-15|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, New Jersey officials reported 80 new positive cases of the coronavirus, bringing the cumulative total to 178 for the state. Three people in New Jersey had died from the virus. Gatherings of 50 or more people were prohibited, in line with federal guidelines. Governor Murphy suggested a statewide curfew of 8 p.m. All bars, casinos, gyms, movie theaters, and restaurants were closed indefinitely on the 16th at 8 p.m., though bars and restaurants were allowed to remain open for delivery or takeout only. Murphy also announced that all of the state's schools, colleges, and universities would close indefinitely on the 18th. By this time, most of the state's school districts had closed already.<ref>[https://6abc.com/6018080/ \"New Jersey Governor confirms 3rd coronavirus-related death\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317183352/https://6abc.com/6018080/ |date=2020-03-17 }}. 6abc.com. March 16, 2020. Retrieved March 17, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 17, it was announced that there were 89 new cases of the coronavirus in New Jersey, bringing the state's total to 267. Among the 267 patients up to that point, about 55% were hospitalized. The patients' ages ranged from 5 to 93, with a median of 52. Governor Murphy said that as of 8 p.m. on the 17th, all of the state's amusement centers, amusement parks, and shopping malls would be closed indefinitely. \"This is a virus unlike everything we've ever seen in our lifetime,\" Murphy said. According to Marilou Halvorsen, the president and CEO of the New Jersey Restaurant and Hospitality Association, 90% of restaurant employees were laid off on the 16th. There were 15,000 unemployment applications filed on the 16th, and the increase caused the computer system at the state Department of Labor to crash.<ref>Washburn, Lindy. [https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/17/coronavirus-update-nj-testing-ramps-up-cases-surge-tuesday-267/5067268002/ \"Coronavirus cases in New Jersey continue surge Tuesday to 267 as testing steps up\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317232328/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/17/coronavirus-update-nj-testing-ramps-up-cases-surge-tuesday-267/5067268002/ |date=2020-03-17 }}. northjersey.com. March 17, 2020. Retrieved March 17, 2020.</ref> In a letter that Governor Murphy sent to President Trump, he indicated that the hospital bed shortage in New Jersey could reach 123,000 to 313,000 beds sometime between May and October. He requested the U.S. military and Army Corps of Engineers to help in expanding the hospital capacity.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Racioppi |first1=Dustin |title=NJ will reopen hospital as state faces massive bed shortfalls with coronavirus spreading |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/18/coronavirus-nj-hospitals-face-bed-shortage-virus-spread-says-gov-phil-murphy/2863566001/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Trenton Bureau |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319172511/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/18/coronavirus-nj-hospitals-face-bed-shortage-virus-spread-says-gov-phil-murphy/2863566001/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 18\u201324 ====\n[[File:New Jersey National Guard - 49692255982.jpg|thumb|A New Jersey National Guard Airman providing traffic control at the PNC Bank Arts Center coronavirus testing site in March 2020.]]\nOn March 18, Governor Murphy announced that there were 160 more positive tests for the coronavirus, bringing New Jersey's total to 427. At that point, cases had been found in 18 of the state's 21 counties. The death toll rose to five, as two more people died. Schools were closed statewide starting on the 18th.<ref>[https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/coronavirus/new-jersey-coronavirus-response/2331440/ \"NJ Coronavirus Cases Jump to 427, 5 People Have Died\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318230227/https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/coronavirus/new-jersey-coronavirus-response/2331440/ |date=2020-03-18 }}. nbcphiladelphia.com. March 18, 2020. Retrieved March 18, 2020.</ref><ref>Lindy Washburn and Dustin Racioppi. [https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/18/coronavirus-update-nj-cases-still-spiking-tests-uptick-now-427/2863699001/ \"NJ reports two more coronavirus-related deaths as statewide cases spike to 427 Wednesday\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318230231/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/18/coronavirus-update-nj-cases-still-spiking-tests-uptick-now-427/2863699001/ |date=2020-03-18 }}. northjersey.com. March 18, 2020. Retrieved March 18, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Governor Murphy announced 315 new positive tests for the coronavirus, bringing the state's total to 742. There were four more deaths, bringing the death toll to nine. Murphy ordered all personal care businesses that could not maintain proper social distancing to close by 8 p.m. on the 19th; these businesses included barbershops, hair salons, nail salons, spas, and tattoo parlors. That day, Murphy said, \"We've basically shut the state down. Stay home.\" Murphy also announced that upcoming local special elections and school board elections would be postponed until May 12, with voting being done by mail. Ridership on the [[New Jersey Transit]] dropped by almost 90% in the previous week, and the agency requested $1.25 billion in federal aid.<ref>[https://6abc.com/6026759/ \"9 total coronavirus deaths in New Jersey; personal care businesses to close\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319194310/https://6abc.com/6026759/ |date=2020-03-19 }}. 6abc.com. March 19, 2020. Retrieved March 20, 2020.</ref><ref>Washburn, Lindy. [https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/19/nj-coronavirus-deaths-rise-9-statewide-cases-reach-742-thursday/2872991001/ \"NJ coronavirus deaths rise to 9, with statewide cases reaching 742 on Thursday\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320052828/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/19/nj-coronavirus-deaths-rise-9-statewide-cases-reach-742-thursday/2872991001/ |date=2020-03-20 }}. northjersey.com. March 19, 2020. Retrieved March 20, 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/coronavirus/new-jersey-coronavirus-spread/2332963/ \"New Coronavirus Cases in NJ Nearly Double, 4 More People Die\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320052830/https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/coronavirus/new-jersey-coronavirus-spread/2332963/ |date=2020-03-20 }}. nbcphiladelphia.com. March 19, 2020. Retrieved March 20, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 20, New Jersey officials said that the number of coronavirus cases in the state rose to 890. Two more deaths were reported, bringing the state's total to 11. Governor Murphy planned to close all non-essential businesses. \"It brings me no joy, but we have no choice. We will, within the next 24 hours, further tighten screws in terms of social distancing,\" Murphy said. Unemployment claims in New Jersey increased 20% for the week ending March 14 compared to the same period the previous year. The first government-run coronavirus testing center opened on the 20th at [[Bergen Community College]] in Bergen County. Hundreds of cars were lined up for about three miles waiting to get into the drive-thru center. It opened at 8 a.m., and by 12 p.m., people were turned away as the center was at capacity. Health workers at the site tested more than 650 people.<ref>O'Neill, James M. [https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/20/coronavirus-update-nj-deaths-11-cases-rise-890/2884916001/ \"Coronavirus NJ: Murphy to announce more restrictions, closures Saturday as deaths reach 11\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321023321/https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/20/coronavirus-update-nj-deaths-11-cases-rise-890/2884916001/ |date=2020-03-21 }}. northjersey.com. March 20, 2020. Retrieved March 20, 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-more-restrictions-coming-nj-cases-jump-to-nearly-900-heres-what-you-need-to-know.html \"Coronavirus updates: More restrictions coming, N.J. cases jump to nearly 900. Here's what you need to know.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321023317/https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-more-restrictions-coming-nj-cases-jump-to-nearly-900-heres-what-you-need-to-know.html |date=2020-03-21 }}. nj.com. March 20, 2020. Retrieved March 20, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 21, New Jersey officials reported over 400 new cases of the coronavirus, bringing the state's total to 1,327. There were five more deaths, bringing the total to 16. By that point, the virus had been found in all 21 of New Jersey's counties. Governor Murphy announced a statewide [[stay-at-home order]] that all non-essential businesses in the state would be closed indefinitely by 9 p.m. on the 21st. The state's libraries were also closed. Police academies were closed until April 6. On March 21, the testing site at Bergen Community College reached its daily capacity of 350 tests within two hours.<ref>Michael Sol Warren. [https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-murphy-orders-residents-to-stay-home-as-new-jersey-reaches-1327-cases-16-deaths.html \"Coronavirus updates: Murphy orders residents to stay home as New Jersey reaches 1,327 cases, 16 deaths\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322033442/https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-murphy-orders-residents-to-stay-home-as-new-jersey-reaches-1327-cases-16-deaths.html |date=2020-03-22 }}. nj.com. March 21, 2020. Retrieved March 21, 2020.</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus in N.J.: What's open, what's closed? Restaurants, stores, banks, mail delivery, malls, UPS, gyms, schools (3/22/2020) |url=https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-in-nj-whats-open-whats-closed-restaurants-stores-banks-mail-delivery-malls-ups-gyms-schools-3222020.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=nj.com |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322202557/https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-in-nj-whats-open-whats-closed-restaurants-stores-banks-mail-delivery-malls-ups-gyms-schools-3222020.html |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy March 23, there were 2,844 cases of the coronavirus in the state. New Jersey had the second-most cases of all states in the country, behind only New York. The death toll in New Jersey increased to 27. New drive-through testing centers opened at [[Hudson Regional Hospital]], [[Kean University]], and [[PNC Bank Arts Center]]. The economy was affected negatively by the coronavirus, and the state prepared for a drop in tax revenue by putting $900 million into reserve.<ref>[https://6abc.com/6044279/ \"New Jersey freezes nearly $1B in state spending because of COVID-19\"]. 6abc.com. March 24, 2020. Retrieved March 24, 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/24/latest-news-coronavirus-nj/4962627002/ \"Coronavirus updates: Bergen Community College testing site reaches capacity early again\"]. northjersey.com. March 24, 2020. Retrieved March 24, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 24, officials announced an increase to 3,675 cases of the coronavirus in New Jersey. The number of deaths rose by 17, to 44 total.<ref>Johnson, Brent. [https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/nj-coronavirus-deaths-increase-to-44-statewide-with-3675-total-cases-846-new-positive-tests-announced.html \"N.J. coronavirus deaths increase to 44 with 3,675 total cases statewide. 846 new positive tests announced.\"]. nj.com. March 24, 2020. Retrieved March 24, 2020.</ref> A 50-year-old [[Freehold Township, New Jersey|Freehold Township]] man was charged with terroristic threats, harassment, and obstruction after he coughed on a [[Wegmans]] supermarket clerk in [[Manalapan Township, New Jersey|Manalapan Township]] and laughingly declared he had the coronavirus.<ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/us/nj-man-who-coughed-wegmans-worker-to-face-charges-of-terroristic-threats-governor-says NJ man who coughed on Wegmans worker to face charges of terroristic threats, governor says] By Louis Casiano, Fox News, 24 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==== March 25\u201331 ====\nOn March 25, confirmed coronavirus cases rose to 4,402. The number of deaths rose by 18, to 62 total.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/new-jersey-coronavirus-cases-surge-to-4402-with-62-deaths-officials-announce-736-new-cases.html|title=New Jersey coronavirus cases surge to 4,402 with 62 deaths. Officials announce 736 new cases.|last=Arco|first=Matt|date=2020-03-25|website=nj|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> All 94 residents of St. Joseph's Senior Home in [[Woodbridge Township, New Jersey|Woodbridge Township]] were assumed to have coronavirus. The first of 24 positive cases was discovered on March 17, and at least one more had developed every day since then.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/entire-senior-home-new-jersey-94-people-presumed-have-coronavirus-n1168701?fbclid=IwAR1rQc9tFdXZU3AFwq1kws-vuapCxf5xI2EYSbagbawR4zOAW70yLOx2y6A Entire senior home in New Jersey, 94 people, presumed to have coronavirus] By David K. Li, NBC News, 25 Mar 2020</ref> A hotline had been set up for New Jersey workers to report employers for making them go to work despite the emergency declaration, but it got so many calls that it crashed the system. The state subsequently set up a website for workers to report violations.<ref name=\"abc7ny\">[https://abc7ny.com/coronavirus-nj-new-jersey-news-update-cases-map/5987040/ \"Coronavirus Updates: New Jersey reports more than 6,800 COVID-19 cases, 81 deaths\"]. abc7ny.com. March 26, 2020. Retrieved March 27, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 26, New Jersey officials announced that the number of coronavirus cases had increased to 6,876. The death toll went up by 19, to 81 in total. Governor Murphy said that 155,000 people filed for unemployment benefits in New Jersey during the previous week, 16 times the number that filed the week before.<ref name=\"abc7ny\"/>\n\nOn March 27, state officials announced that there were 8,825 known cases of the coronavirus. The number of deaths increased by 27, to 108. Since the outbreak started, New Jersey's state laboratory had run 28,043 coronavirus tests with 8,296 positive ones for a rate of 33.4%. At least one positive test had been found in 55 of the state's 375 nursing homes.<ref>Brent Johnson and Len Melisurgo. [https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/nj-coronavirus-cases-spike-to-8825-with-108-deaths-officials-announce-1982-new-positive-tests-marking-another-big-24-hour-surge.html \"N.J. coronavirus cases spike to 8,825 with 108 deaths. Officials announce 1,982 new positive tests, marking another big 24-hour surge.\"]. nj.com. March 27, 2020. Retrieved March 28, 2020.</ref> Police broke up a house party with 47 people crammed into a small apartment in [[Ewing Township, New Jersey|Ewing Township]]. The organizer was charged.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/police-break-illegal-house-party-230149365.html Police break up 'illegal' house party that violated N.J.'s stay-at-home order] by Nicole Acevedo, NBC Today, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 29, New Jersey announced that there were 13,386 cases of the coronavirus in the state, including 161 deaths. New Jersey had the second-largest outbreak in the country, behind only New York. In a Twitter video, Governor Murphy said, \"Nothing's changed in New Jersey, stay at home. New Jersey is part of the hottest spot in America right now, alongside New York City and the nation's eyes are upon us.\"<ref>Gomez, Jessie. [https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2020/03/29/coronavirus-nj-over-13-000-positive-tests-state/2935639001/ \"Coronavirus NJ: Positive cases over 13,000 with most in Bergen as deaths reach 161\"]. northjersey.com. March 29, 2020. Retrieved March 30, 2020.</ref> According to the acting superintendent of New Jersey's state police, about 700 police officers in the state had tested positive for the coronavirus, but none had died.<ref>[https://6abc.com/new-jersey-disaster-declaration-coronavirus-nj-death-rate-cases/6060853/ \"New Jersey Gov. Phil Murphy asks for more ventilators as COVID-19 cases climb to more than 13,000 across state\"]. 6abc.com. March 29, 2020. Retrieved March 30, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 30, New Jersey announced that the total number of cases had rose to 16,636. The death toll increased by 37, to 198.<ref>Arco, Matt. [https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/new-jersey-coronavirus-cases-increase-to-16636-with-198-deaths-officials-announce-over-3k-new-positive-tests.html \"New Jersey coronavirus cases increase to 16,636 with 198 deaths. Officials announce 3,347 new positive tests.\"]. nj.com. March 30, 2020. Retrieved March 30, 2020.</ref>\n\nOn March 31, Governor Murphy announced that there were 18,696 cases of the coronavirus in New Jersey. The death toll increased by 69, to 267.<ref>Johnson, Brent. [https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/nj-coronavirus-deaths-surge-to-267-with-18696-total-cases-more-than-2k-new-positive-tests-reported.html \"N.J. coronavirus deaths surge to 267 with 18,696 total cases. More than 2K new positive tests reported.\"]. nj.com. March 31, 2020. Retrieved April 1, 2020.</ref> By this time, police in Newark had closed 16 nonessential businesses and issued over 250 summonses for obstructing the business of law. The Ocean County towns of Bay Head, Mantoloking, and Point Pleasant Beach decided to close their beaches starting April 3 to slow the spread of the virus.<ref>[https://6abc.com/health/new-jersey-death-toll-from-covid-19-approaching-300-/6064948/ \"New Jersey death toll from COVID-19 approaching 300\"]. 6abc.com. March 31, 2020. Retrieved April 1, 2020.</ref>\n\n===April===\n====April 1\u20137====\nOn April 1, Governor Murphy announced that there were 22,255 coronavirus cases in New Jersey, including 355 deaths. State lawmakers moved New Jersey's income tax deadline from April 15 to July 15 and moved New Jersey's budget deadline from June 30 to September 30. According to the lawmakers, \"The ongoing COVID-19 pandemic has caused hardships, financial strain, and disruptions for many New Jerseyans and New Jersey businesses.\"<ref>[https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/coronavirus/new-jersey-taxes-coronavirus/2348520/ \"NJ Announces Thousands More Coronavirus Cases, 91 New Deaths\"]. nbcphiladelphia.com. April 1, 2020. Retrieved April 1, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nOn March 12, the [[National Hockey League]] season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 New Jersey Devils season|New Jersey Devils]].<ref name=\"nhl\">[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=2020-03-14 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref> In college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=\"ncaa\">[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=2020-03-12 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=2020-03-18 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/New Jersey medical cases chart}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in New Jersey<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldman |first1=Jeff |title=Where is coronavirus in N.J. right now? Latest map, county-by-county list. (March 22, 2020) |url=https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/where-is-coronavirus-in-nj-right-now-latest-map-county-by-county-list-march-22-2020.html |website=www.nj.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323000301/https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/where-is-coronavirus-in-nj-right-now-latest-map-county-by-county-list-march-22-2020.html |archivedate=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://projects.nj.com/coronavirus-tracker/|title=N.J. coronavirus tracker (live map)|website=NJ.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\nUpdated April 2, 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/coronavirus/2020/03/where-is-the-coronavirus-in-nj-latest-map-update-on-county-by-county-cases-march-26-2020.html|title=Where is the coronavirus in N.J.? Latest map, update on county-by-county cases. (March 26, 2020)|last=|first=|date=|website=Nj.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed cases\n!Deaths\n!Recoveries\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Atlantic County, New Jersey|Atlantic]]\n|40\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen]]\n|3,494\n|75\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Burlington County, New Jersey|Burlington]]\n|255\n|5\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Camden County, New Jersey|Camden]]\n|289\n|3\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cape May County, New Jersey|Cape May]]\n|22\n|0\n|5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cumberla